@MadeYouType  Consistency is more important than efficiency.  Easier methods that don't require perfection allow for earlier consistency. Once you achieve consistency, you can start building familiarity. Once you are familiar, you can slowly upgrade your safe techniques one by one to more efficient and riskier ones. Because you have built familiarity, you do not panic if you mess up and know how to correct for those mistakes.

Nearly every real life skill works on this basis. You build foundations, then you build consistency in those foundations and only once you are capable of independent problem solving do you begin doing advanced techniques.

No chemist starts their career performing modern metallorganic synthesis. No chemist starts their career operating an NMR or matrix-isolation IR. They start with salt and water to learn crystalization and titrations.

